{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b637347d-9e93-4ca5-923b-cce54490f81a","content":"This is a TUnit project (MTP-native). Use the `--treenode-filter` to filter by class:\n\n```bash\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe tree-node path format is `/assembly/namespace/class/test`, so `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches all tests in the `SmsNotificationTests` class regardless of assembly or namespace.\n\nAlternatively, with `dotnet test`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0933c106-18ba-4899-addc-2ecd33c21f2e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax to filter by class is `--treenode-filter` with a specific syntax.\n\nFor TUnit (which uses MTP), to filter by class name:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nOr using `dotnet test` - but TUnit is an MTP-native framework. Let me think about this...\n\nTUnit projects with `OutputType: Exe` are MTP-native. The way to run them is either:\n\n\n1. `dotnet run` with `--treenode-filter`\n2. `dotnet test` with appropriate filters\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, the treenode filter follows the pattern `/assembly/namespace/class/test`, so filtering by class name `SmsNotificationTests` would use the syntax with wildcards to match all tests under that class.","outputTokens":689},"id":"23a19a12-f9a4-4fad-b5a7-da4a66ef241e","timestamp":"2026-04-07T15:58:17.530Z","parentId":"5d4aba88-29e8-4bb6-963c-dc5dc6a17cc0"}
